<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!--
  Appendix: Argument Diagrams.
  Optional visual supplement to Chapter 2's verbal reconstruction method.
-->
<appendix xml:id="appendix-diagramming">

  <title>Argument Diagrams</title>

  <introduction>
    <p>
      Argument diagrams are optional. They give a visual overview of an
      argument's structure, but they do not replace the reconstruction.
      The reconstruction remains the primary form because it states every
      claim and every support relation in words.
    </p>
    <p>
      The diagrams in this appendix use compact labels such as P1, P2,
      C1, and C. The full reconstruction appears with each diagram. If
      you cannot see or do not want to use the diagram, the reconstruction
      gives the same structural information in words.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <section xml:id="sec-diagramming-conventions">
    <title>Diagramming Conventions</title>

    <introduction>
      <p>
        The conventions are simple. Arrows show support. A bracket shows
        that statements support a conclusion dependently. Separate arrows
        into the same conclusion show independent support. A single
        statement can also support more than one later conclusion.
      </p>
    </introduction>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-diagram-single-arrow">
      <title>Single support</title>
      <p>
        When one statement supports another statement, draw one arrow
        from the supporting statement to the supported statement.
      </p>
      <p>
        Reconstruction:
      </p>
      <p>P1: The seminar meets in Monroe Hall.</p>
      <p>C: The seminar meets on campus. (from P1)</p>
      <figure xml:id="fig-diagram-single-arrow">
        <caption>A single arrow from P1 to C.</caption>
        <image xml:id="image-diagram-single-arrow" width="50%">
          <description>
            <p>
              A diagram with P1 on the left and C on the right. One
              arrow runs from P1 to C, indicating that P1 supports C.
            </p>
          </description>
          <latex-image>
            \begin{tikzpicture}[x=1cm,y=1cm,>=stealth]
              \tikzstyle{statement}=[draw,rounded corners=2pt,minimum width=1.2cm,minimum height=0.55cm,align=center,inner sep=4pt]
              \node[statement] (p1) at (0,0) {$P1$};
              \node[statement] (c) at (3,0) {$C$};
              \draw[->,thick] (p1) -- (c);
            \end{tikzpicture}
          </latex-image>
        </image>
      </figure>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-diagram-dependent-support">
      <title>Dependent support</title>
      <p>
        When two or more statements have to work together, group them
        with a bracket and draw one arrow from the bracket to the
        conclusion.
      </p>
      <p>
        Reconstruction:
      </p>
      <p>
        P1: If the only available exam time conflicts with a required
        lab, the department should offer a make-up exam.
      </p>
      <p>
        P2: The only available exam time conflicts with a required lab.
      </p>
      <p>
        C: The department should offer a make-up exam. (from P1 and P2,
        which are dependent)
      </p>
      <figure xml:id="fig-diagram-dependent-support">
        <caption>A bracket groups P1 and P2; one arrow runs from the bracket to C.</caption>
        <image xml:id="image-diagram-dependent-support" width="60%">
          <description>
            <p>
              P1 appears above P2 on the left. A bracket groups P1
              and P2 together. One arrow leaves the bracket and points
              to C, indicating that P1 and P2 support C dependently.
            </p>
          </description>
          <latex-image>
            \begin{tikzpicture}[x=1cm,y=1cm,>=stealth]
              \tikzstyle{statement}=[draw,rounded corners=2pt,minimum width=1.2cm,minimum height=0.55cm,align=center,inner sep=4pt]
              \node[statement] (p1) at (0,0.45) {$P1$};
              \node[statement] (p2) at (0,-0.45) {$P2$};
              \node[statement] (c) at (3.2,0) {$C$};
              \draw[thick] (0.85,0.75) -- (1.1,0.75) -- (1.1,-0.75) -- (0.85,-0.75);
              \draw[->,thick] (1.1,0) -- (c);
            \end{tikzpicture}
          </latex-image>
        </image>
      </figure>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-diagram-independent-support">
      <title>Independent support</title>
      <p>
        When two or more statements each give support on their own, draw
        a separate arrow from each supporting statement to the conclusion.
      </p>
      <p>
        Reconstruction:
      </p>
      <p>P1: The early bus is usually less crowded.</p>
      <p>
        P2: The early bus gets to campus before the coffee line gets
        ridiculous.
      </p>
      <p>C: You should take the early bus. (from P1 and P2 independently)</p>
      <figure xml:id="fig-diagram-independent-support">
        <caption>Separate arrows from P1 and P2 to C.</caption>
        <image xml:id="image-diagram-independent-support" width="60%">
          <description>
            <p>
              P1 appears above P2 on the left, and C appears on the
              right. One arrow runs from P1 to C. A separate arrow runs
              from P2 to C. The separate arrows indicate independent
              support.
            </p>
          </description>
          <latex-image>
            \begin{tikzpicture}[x=1cm,y=1cm,>=stealth]
              \tikzstyle{statement}=[draw,rounded corners=2pt,minimum width=1.2cm,minimum height=0.55cm,align=center,inner sep=4pt]
              \node[statement] (p1) at (0,0.55) {$P1$};
              \node[statement] (p2) at (0,-0.55) {$P2$};
              \node[statement] (c) at (3.2,0) {$C$};
              \draw[->,thick] (p1) -- (c);
              \draw[->,thick] (p2) -- (c);
            \end{tikzpicture}
          </latex-image>
        </image>
      </figure>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-diagram-divergent-support">
      <title>Divergent support</title>
      <p>
        Sometimes one statement supports more than one later conclusion.
        In that case, draw more than one arrow out of the same statement.
      </p>
      <p>
        Reconstruction:
      </p>
      <p>P1: The main quad will be closed for repairs this week.</p>
      <p>
        C1: The outdoor club should move its information table to the
        student center. (from P1)
      </p>
      <p>
        C2: First-year orientation should change its walking route.
        (from P1)
      </p>
      <figure xml:id="fig-diagram-divergent-support">
        <caption>One premise supports two conclusions.</caption>
        <image xml:id="image-diagram-divergent-support" width="60%">
          <description>
            <p>
              P1 appears on the left. C1 appears above C2 on the right.
              One arrow runs from P1 to C1, and another arrow runs from
              P1 to C2. The two outgoing arrows indicate that P1 supports
              more than one conclusion.
            </p>
          </description>
          <latex-image>
            \begin{tikzpicture}[x=1cm,y=1cm,>=stealth]
              \tikzstyle{statement}=[draw,rounded corners=2pt,minimum width=1.2cm,minimum height=0.55cm,align=center,inner sep=4pt]
              \node[statement] (p1) at (0,0) {$P1$};
              \node[statement] (c1) at (3.2,0.55) {$C1$};
              \node[statement] (c2) at (3.2,-0.55) {$C2$};
              \draw[->,thick] (p1) -- (c1);
              \draw[->,thick] (p1) -- (c2);
            \end{tikzpicture}
          </latex-image>
        </image>
      </figure>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-diagram-layered-support">
      <title>Layered support</title>
      <p>
        Layered arguments combine the same conventions. A premise may
        support a sub-conclusion, and that sub-conclusion may then help
        support a later conclusion.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-diagramming-worked-examples">
    <title>Worked Examples</title>

    <introduction>
      <p>
        The examples below come from Chapters 1 and 2. The reconstruction
        states the structure. The diagram shows the same structure
        visually.
      </p>
    </introduction>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-diagram-library">
      <title>The library is closed</title>
      <p>
        Reconstruction:
      </p>
      <p>P1: The library closes at nine.</p>
      <p>P2: It is now ten past nine.</p>
      <p>C: The library is closed. (from P1 and P2, which are dependent)</p>
      <figure xml:id="fig-diagram-library">
        <caption>The library argument diagrammed as dependent support.</caption>
        <image xml:id="image-diagram-library" width="60%">
          <description>
            <p>
              P1 and P2 are grouped by a bracket. One arrow leaves the
              bracket and points to C. The bracket indicates that P1 and
              P2 work together to support C dependently.
            </p>
          </description>
          <latex-image>
            \begin{tikzpicture}[x=1cm,y=1cm,>=stealth]
              \tikzstyle{statement}=[draw,rounded corners=2pt,minimum width=1.2cm,minimum height=0.55cm,align=center,inner sep=4pt]
              \node[statement] (p1) at (0,0.45) {$P1$};
              \node[statement] (p2) at (0,-0.45) {$P2$};
              \node[statement] (c) at (3.2,0) {$C$};
              \draw[thick] (0.85,0.75) -- (1.1,0.75) -- (1.1,-0.75) -- (0.85,-0.75);
              \draw[->,thick] (1.1,0) -- (c);
            \end{tikzpicture}
          </latex-image>
        </image>
      </figure>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-diagram-god-mt">
      <title>An argument for God's existence</title>
      <p>
        Reconstruction:
      </p>
      <p>P1: If there is no God, then life is meaningless.</p>
      <p>P2: Life is not meaningless.</p>
      <p>C: God exists. (from P1 and P2, which are dependent)</p>
      <figure xml:id="fig-diagram-god-mt">
        <caption>The modus tollens argument diagrammed as dependent support.</caption>
        <image xml:id="image-diagram-god-mt" width="60%">
          <description>
            <p>
              P1 and P2 are grouped by a bracket. One arrow leaves the
              bracket and points to C. The bracket indicates that the
              conditional premise and the denial of its consequent work
              together to support the conclusion.
            </p>
          </description>
          <latex-image>
            \begin{tikzpicture}[x=1cm,y=1cm,>=stealth]
              \tikzstyle{statement}=[draw,rounded corners=2pt,minimum width=1.2cm,minimum height=0.55cm,align=center,inner sep=4pt]
              \node[statement] (p1) at (0,0.45) {$P1$};
              \node[statement] (p2) at (0,-0.45) {$P2$};
              \node[statement] (c) at (3.2,0) {$C$};
              \draw[thick] (0.85,0.75) -- (1.1,0.75) -- (1.1,-0.75) -- (0.85,-0.75);
              \draw[->,thick] (1.1,0) -- (c);
            \end{tikzpicture}
          </latex-image>
        </image>
      </figure>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-diagram-god-mp">
      <title>An argument against God's existence</title>
      <p>
        Reconstruction:
      </p>
      <p>P1: If there is evil in the world, then God does not exist.</p>
      <p>P2: There is evil in the world.</p>
      <p>C: God does not exist. (from P1 and P2, which are dependent)</p>
      <figure xml:id="fig-diagram-god-mp">
        <caption>The modus ponens argument diagrammed as dependent support.</caption>
        <image xml:id="image-diagram-god-mp" width="60%">
          <description>
            <p>
              P1 and P2 are grouped by a bracket. One arrow leaves the
              bracket and points to C. The bracket indicates that the
              conditional premise and the affirmation of its antecedent
              work together to support the conclusion.
            </p>
          </description>
          <latex-image>
            \begin{tikzpicture}[x=1cm,y=1cm,>=stealth]
              \tikzstyle{statement}=[draw,rounded corners=2pt,minimum width=1.2cm,minimum height=0.55cm,align=center,inner sep=4pt]
              \node[statement] (p1) at (0,0.45) {$P1$};
              \node[statement] (p2) at (0,-0.45) {$P2$};
              \node[statement] (c) at (3.2,0) {$C$};
              \draw[thick] (0.85,0.75) -- (1.1,0.75) -- (1.1,-0.75) -- (0.85,-0.75);
              \draw[->,thick] (1.1,0) -- (c);
            \end{tikzpicture}
          </latex-image>
        </image>
      </figure>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-diagram-running-shoes">
      <title>Running shoes</title>
      <p>
        Reconstruction:
      </p>
      <p>
        P1: Archaeologists have found rope-soled sandals from twenty
        thousand years ago with wear patterns associated with running.
      </p>
      <p>
        P2: Similar running-adapted sandals have appeared independently
        in widely separated cultures.
      </p>
      <p>
        C: The deliberate design of footwear for running is a much older
        human practice than people assume. (from P1 and P2 independently)
      </p>
      <p>
        This reconstruction treats P1 and P2 as independent support.
        There are probably alternative correct ways to diagram this
        argument, provided the reconstruction explains the support
        relation clearly.
      </p>
      <figure xml:id="fig-diagram-running-shoes">
        <caption>The running shoes argument diagrammed as independent support.</caption>
        <image xml:id="image-diagram-running-shoes" width="60%">
          <description>
            <p>
              P1 appears above P2 on the left. C appears on the right.
              A separate arrow runs from P1 to C, and another separate
              arrow runs from P2 to C. The separate arrows indicate that
              P1 and P2 are being treated as independent support.
            </p>
          </description>
          <latex-image>
            \begin{tikzpicture}[x=1cm,y=1cm,>=stealth]
              \tikzstyle{statement}=[draw,rounded corners=2pt,minimum width=1.2cm,minimum height=0.55cm,align=center,inner sep=4pt]
              \node[statement] (p1) at (0,0.55) {$P1$};
              \node[statement] (p2) at (0,-0.55) {$P2$};
              \node[statement] (c) at (3.2,0) {$C$};
              \draw[->,thick] (p1) -- (c);
              \draw[->,thick] (p2) -- (c);
            \end{tikzpicture}
          </latex-image>
        </image>
      </figure>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-diagram-food-pantry">
      <title>The campus food pantry</title>
      <p>
        Reconstruction:
      </p>
      <p>P1: The campus food pantry buys staple foods in bulk.</p>
      <p>
        C1: Each dollar donated to the campus food pantry goes farther
        than it would at a grocery store. (from P1)
      </p>
      <p>P2: The campus food pantry lets students choose what they need.</p>
      <p>
        C2: The campus food pantry respects students' dignity and reduces
        waste. (from P2)
      </p>
      <p>
        P3: Programs that use money efficiently and respect the people
        they serve deserve support.
      </p>
      <p>
        C: You should donate to the campus food pantry. (from C1, C2,
        and P3, which are dependent)
      </p>
      <figure xml:id="fig-diagram-food-pantry">
        <caption>The food pantry argument diagrammed as a layered argument.</caption>
        <image xml:id="image-diagram-food-pantry" width="75%">
          <description>
            <p>
              P1 points to C1, showing that P1 supports the first
              sub-conclusion. P2 points to C2, showing that P2 supports
              the second sub-conclusion. C1, C2, and P3 are then grouped
              by a bracket, and one arrow leaves that bracket and points
              to C. The final bracket indicates that C1, C2, and P3
              support the final conclusion dependently.
            </p>
          </description>
          <latex-image>
            \begin{tikzpicture}[x=1cm,y=1cm,>=stealth]
              \tikzstyle{statement}=[draw,rounded corners=2pt,minimum width=1.15cm,minimum height=0.55cm,align=center,inner sep=4pt]
              \node[statement] (p1) at (0,1.0) {$P1$};
              \node[statement] (c1) at (2.3,1.0) {$C1$};
              \node[statement] (p2) at (0,0) {$P2$};
              \node[statement] (c2) at (2.3,0) {$C2$};
              \node[statement] (p3) at (2.3,-1.0) {$P3$};
              \node[statement] (c) at (5.4,0) {$C$};
              \draw[->,thick] (p1) -- (c1);
              \draw[->,thick] (p2) -- (c2);
              \draw[thick] (3.05,1.3) -- (3.3,1.3) -- (3.3,-1.3) -- (3.05,-1.3);
              \draw[->,thick] (3.3,0) -- (c);
            \end{tikzpicture}
          </latex-image>
        </image>
      </figure>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-diagram-oxfam">
      <title>Oxfam, revisited</title>
      <p>
        Reconstruction:
      </p>
      <p>P1: 89 cents of every dollar goes directly to organizations on the ground.</p>
      <p>P2: The aid provides for things like goats and schoolbooks.</p>
      <p>
        C1: The aid Oxfam provides makes it so a family can provide for
        itself and the next generation has options. (from P2)
      </p>
      <p>
        C2: Oxfam efficiently uses contributions to help end long-term
        poverty by providing the tools for people to get an education and
        support their families. (from P1 and C1, which are dependent)
      </p>
      <p>P3: It feels good to help people.</p>
      <p>
        P4: You should donate to programs that efficiently end long-term
        poverty and that you find rewarding to support. (implicit)
      </p>
      <p>
        C3: You should donate to Oxfam. (from C2, P3, and P4, which are
        dependent)
      </p>
      <p>
        This diagram keeps P3 as part of the argument and supplies an
        implicit bridging premise. A more critical reconstruction might
        treat P3 as rhetorical rather than as a premise.
      </p>
      <figure xml:id="fig-diagram-oxfam">
        <caption>The Oxfam argument diagrammed with layered dependent support.</caption>
        <image xml:id="image-diagram-oxfam" width="80%">
          <description>
            <p>
              P2 points to C1. P1 and C1 are grouped by a bracket, and
              one arrow leaves that bracket and points to C2, indicating
              dependent support. C2, P3, and P4 are then grouped by a
              second bracket, and one arrow leaves that bracket and points
              to C3, indicating dependent support for the final conclusion.
            </p>
          </description>
          <latex-image>
            \begin{tikzpicture}[x=1cm,y=1cm,>=stealth]
              \tikzstyle{statement}=[draw,rounded corners=2pt,minimum width=1.15cm,minimum height=0.55cm,align=center,inner sep=4pt]
              \node[statement] (p2) at (0,0) {$P2$};
              \node[statement] (c1) at (2.1,0) {$C1$};
              \node[statement] (p1) at (2.1,1.0) {$P1$};
              \node[statement] (c2) at (4.6,0.5) {$C2$};
              \node[statement] (p3) at (4.6,-0.5) {$P3$};
              \node[statement] (p4) at (4.6,-1.5) {$P4$};
              \node[statement] (c3) at (7.8,-0.5) {$C3$};
              \draw[->,thick] (p2) -- (c1);
              \draw[thick] (2.85,1.3) -- (3.1,1.3) -- (3.1,-0.3) -- (2.85,-0.3);
              \draw[->,thick] (3.1,0.5) -- (c2);
              \draw[thick] (5.35,0.8) -- (5.6,0.8) -- (5.6,-1.8) -- (5.35,-1.8);
              \draw[->,thick] (5.6,-0.5) -- (c3);
            \end{tikzpicture}
          </latex-image>
        </image>
      </figure>
    </paragraphs>

  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-diagramming-accessibility">
    <title>Accessibility Note</title>

    <p>
      Every diagram in this appendix has a text description that states
      the support structure in words. Those descriptions are not a
      secondary version of the argument. They express the same structure
      the reconstruction already states: which claims support which
      conclusions, and whether the support is dependent or independent.
      Nothing in the course assessments depends on producing or reading
      a visual argument diagram.
    </p>

  </section>

  <exercises xml:id="exercises-appendix-diagramming">
    <title>Optional Exercises</title>

    <introduction>
      <p>
        These exercises are optional practice. For each one, start with
        a verbal reconstruction. Then draw a diagram that matches the
        reconstruction. Your diagram should not contain information that
        is missing from the reconstruction.
      </p>
    </introduction>

    <exercisegroup xml:id="exgroup-appendix-diagramming-practice">
      <title>Diagramming Practice</title>

      <exercise xml:id="ex-appendix-diagramming-01">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Choose one reconstruction from Chapter 2 that has dependent
            support. Draw the diagram and write one sentence explaining
            why the premises are grouped.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>

      <exercise xml:id="ex-appendix-diagramming-02">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Choose one reconstruction from Chapter 2 that has independent
            support. Draw the diagram and write one sentence explaining
            why the arrows are separate.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>

      <exercise xml:id="ex-appendix-diagramming-03">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Diagram the food pantry argument from Chapter 2 without
            looking back at the diagram in this appendix. Then compare
            your diagram with the one above. If they differ, decide
            whether the difference is a real structural disagreement or
            only a difference in layout.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>

      <exercise xml:id="ex-appendix-diagramming-04">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Write a short argument in which one premise supports two
            different conclusions. Reconstruct it, then draw the divergent
            diagram.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>

      <exercise xml:id="ex-appendix-diagramming-05">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Find a passage from outside this book that contains at least
            one sub-conclusion. Reconstruct it in words first. Then draw
            a diagram only after the verbal reconstruction is complete.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>

    </exercisegroup>

  </exercises>

</appendix>
